import{_ as t,o as a,c as i,ag as n}from"./chunks/framework.DmWB24NN.js";const m=JSON.parse('{"title":"CHAPTER 7: NON-COMBAT SKILLS","description":"","frontmatter":{},"headers":[],"relativePath":"Book I - Core Rules/B01 - Chapter 07_ Non-Combat Skills.md","filePath":"Book I - Core Rules/B01 - Chapter 07_ Non-Combat Skills.md"}'),r={name:"Book I - Core Rules/B01 - Chapter 07_ Non-Combat Skills.md"};function s(o,e,l,d,c,h){return a(),i("div",null,[...e[0]||(e[0]=[n('<h1 id="chapter-7-non-combat-skills" tabindex="-1"><strong>CHAPTER 7: NON-COMBAT SKILLS</strong> <a class="header-anchor" href="#chapter-7-non-combat-skills" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;**CHAPTER 7: NON-COMBAT SKILLS**&quot;">​</a></h1><p>Skills define what a character can do beyond their class training. A Fighter who grew up on a Bellarian fishing coast knows things about tides, knots, and weather that their sword arm never taught them. A Thief who spent years working the Solaran court has social fluency that no amount of backstab practice produces. Skills are the history, the life a character had before adventuring, and the things they learned along the way.</p><hr><h2 id="how-non-combat-skills-work" tabindex="-1"><strong>How Non-Combat Skills Work</strong> <a class="header-anchor" href="#how-non-combat-skills-work" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;**How Non-Combat Skills Work**&quot;">​</a></h2><p>A skill check is a roll of 1d20 against the relevant ability score. If the result is equal to or less than the ability score, the check succeeds.</p><p><strong>Trained:</strong> Roll 1d20 vs. attribute. A success can produce work of genuine quality — the difference between a functional result and a skilled one.</p><p><strong>Untrained:</strong> Roll 1d20+4 vs. attribute. An untrained character attempting a skill they have not invested in rolls with a built-in difficulty offset of 4. Even a success produces only a basic, functional result.</p><p><strong>Specialized:</strong> Some skills cannot be attempted untrained at all. These are marked with a ◆ symbol throughout the skill descriptions. Medicine, Spellcraft, Engineering, and similar disciplines represent bodies of knowledge that cannot be improvised. A character without the relevant skill simply cannot attempt them.</p><p><strong>Favorable and unfavorable conditions:</strong> When circumstances meaningfully improve or worsen the task, the GM adds +2 or +4 to the attribute (easier) or subtracts 2 or 4 (harder) before the roll is made. These are GM calls, not per-skill modifiers. They apply equally to trained and untrained attempts.</p><p><strong>1 is always a success. 20 is always a failure</strong>, regardless of attribute scores or modifiers.</p><h3 id="quality-of-success" tabindex="-1"><strong>Quality of Success</strong> <a class="header-anchor" href="#quality-of-success" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;**Quality of Success**&quot;">​</a></h3><p>A trained character&#39;s success can achieve work of real skill. An untrained character&#39;s success achieves a functional result. This distinction matters at the margin — a trained healer treating a wound and an untrained one doing the same thing both succeed on a roll, but the trained healer&#39;s patient recovers better. The GM applies this principle rather than a mechanical modifier: the quality ceiling is lower for untrained attempts, not the probability of a basic success.</p><hr><h2 id="when-not-to-roll" tabindex="-1"><strong>When Not to Roll</strong> <a class="header-anchor" href="#when-not-to-roll" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;**When Not to Roll**&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Most tasks do not require a skill check. Anyone can cook something edible, swim to stay afloat, recognize a common plant, or fashion a crude splint. A skill roll is called for when the results are genuinely uncertain, and the outcome matters — when failure would be dramatic, when the quality of success is in question, or when time pressure makes the attempt meaningful.</p><p>The GM should not call for rolls on routine activities. A carpenter building a simple table does not roll. A carpenter building a table that needs to hold a specific weight for a specific noble, with substandard materials and half the time they would normally need, rolls.</p><hr><h2 id="ability-score-checks" tabindex="-1"><strong>Ability Score Checks</strong> <a class="header-anchor" href="#ability-score-checks" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;**Ability Score Checks**&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Some situations call for a roll without a specific skill attached — maintaining balance on a slippery deck, spotting movement in a crowded room, catching a falling object. These are ability checks: roll 1d20 against the relevant attribute. The GM assigns the appropriate attribute for the situation. No skill investment is required, and no trained/untrained distinction applies — these represent raw capability, not trained expertise.</p><hr><h2 id="aiding-another" tabindex="-1"><strong>Aiding Another</strong> <a class="header-anchor" href="#aiding-another" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;**Aiding Another**&quot;">​</a></h2><p>When multiple characters work together, the character with the highest relevant skill makes the roll. A second character who is trained in the same skill may assist: on a successful assist check, the primary character gains +2 to their attribute for the roll. Only one character may assist at a time.</p><p>If the assisting character rolls a 20, they impose a −2 penalty instead — they got in the way.</p><p>Some skills cannot be assisted, either because the task is solitary by nature or because intervention would be counterproductive. The GM has final judgment. Assisting a skill check always requires proficiency in that skill; assisting an ability check requires only that the situation permits it.</p><hr><h2 id="optional-rule-additional-skill-points" tabindex="-1"><strong>Optional Rule: Additional Skill Points</strong> <a class="header-anchor" href="#optional-rule-additional-skill-points" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;**Optional Rule: Additional Skill Points**&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Adventurers receive few skill points by design — their primary specialization is adventuring, and the class system reflects that. Players who want more self-sufficient characters may use the following variant: characters receive their starting skill point total again every 3rd or 4th level (GM&#39;s choice). This increases breadth but reduces the differentiation between specialists. When multiple characters share equal proficiency in a skill, only the most proficient character rolls for group tasks.</p><hr><h2 id="skill-descriptions" tabindex="-1"><strong>Skill Descriptions</strong> <a class="header-anchor" href="#skill-descriptions" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;**Skill Descriptions**&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Skills are organized into four categories: General skills (any class), class-specific skills (listed by applicable group), Knowledge skills, and Trade skills. Each entry lists: applicable classes, governing attribute, any built-in difficulty modifier, and skill point cost.</p><p>A skill tagged with ◆ cannot be attempted untrained.</p><hr><h3 id="general-skills" tabindex="-1"><strong>GENERAL SKILLS</strong> <a class="header-anchor" href="#general-skills" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;**GENERAL SKILLS**&quot;">​</a></h3><hr><p><strong>Acrobatics</strong> <em>(Rogue; Dexterity; 0; 1 point)</em> Balance, tumbling, and controlled movement. Acrobats can use this skill in place of a performance to earn income. Cannot be used while more than lightly encumbered.</p><ul><li><em>Defensive Roll:</em> By not attacking in a round, the character improves their AC by 4 for that round.</li><li><em>Quick Attack:</em> When fighting unarmed, a trained acrobat gains +2 to attack rolls.</li><li><em>Tuck-and-Roll:</em> A character falling 18 m or less halves damage on a successful check. A fall of less than 6 m deals no damage on success.</li><li><em>Balance:</em> Maintain footing on surfaces no wider than 15 cm with a +0 check; surfaces of 3 cm or less impose −10; 5–15 cm, −5. A character may fight while balancing at −5 to attack. Damage while balancing requires an immediate check, or the character falls.</li></ul><hr><p><strong>Animal Handling</strong> <em>(General; Wisdom; −1; 2 points)</em> Rearing, taming, and training animals, mundane and magical. Rangers and Druids pay 1 point instead of 2.</p><ul><li><em>Calm Animal:</em> Soothes a frightened or agitated non-magical animal. Does not stop a predator driven by hunger.</li><li><em>Train Animal:</em> An animal can learn a combination of 2d4 tasks and tricks. Tasks (general commands like <em>guard</em> or <em>fetch</em>) take 1d3 months. Tricks take 2d6 weeks. A skill check at the end of training determines success.</li><li><em>Magical creatures</em> and those with animal intelligence can be trained at −4 and must be tamed while young after a month of uninterrupted work.</li></ul><hr><p><strong>Charioteer</strong> <em>(General; Dexterity; 0; 1 point)</em> Operation of wheeled vehicles drawn by animals. A trained charioteer automatically improves chariot speed by one-third, up to the mount&#39;s maximum. Difficult maneuvers require a check. Warriors gain +2 to this skill.</p><hr><p><strong>Climbing</strong> <em>(General; Strength; 0; 1 point — Untrained permitted)</em> A full description of climbing rules appears in Chapter 10. A trained climber gains +10% to their base climb chance per skill point (maximum +30% for mastery). Thieves use their Thief skill for climbing without equipment; this NWP applies to assisted or equipped climbing.</p><hr><p><strong>Disguise</strong> <em>(Rogue; Charisma; −1; 1 point — Untrained permitted)</em> Altering appearance with cosmetics and clothing. Height can be adjusted by up to 30 cm. Race, sex, or age category changes each impose an additional −2 (cumulative). The GM rolls disguise checks in secret. A disguise holds unless an observer has reason for suspicion, at which point they receive a Wisdom check modified by the disguise&#39;s margin of success.</p><hr><p><strong>Endurance</strong> <em>(Rogue/Warrior; Constitution; 0; 2 points)</em> Sustained physical exertion at twice the normal duration — running, swimming, holding breath, and similar activities. Extremely strenuous activities beyond normal capacity require a check.</p><hr><p><strong>Etiquette</strong> <em>(General; Charisma; 0; 1 point)</em> Proper conduct in formal, noble, and diplomatic settings. Unusual or once-in-a-career situations — meeting a foreign dignitary, addressing an extraplanar being, navigating an unfamiliar culture&#39;s formal hierarchy — require a check. The GM should give trained characters appropriate hints; the character knows more than the player does in these situations. The skill does not replace roleplaying — knowing the rules of a social encounter does not prevent a character from being genuinely offensive.</p><hr><p><strong>Jumping</strong> <em>(Rogue; Strength; 0; 1 point — Untrained permitted)</em> A trained jumper performs exceptional leaps without a skill check. Untrained characters jump at half the distances listed.</p><p>Jump distances use the notation <strong>result × 30 cm</strong>, where the result is the dice roll plus any modifiers. Roll the dice, add the modifiers, then multiply by 30 cm.</p><ul><li><em>Broad Jump (6 m running start):</em> (2d6 + level) × 30 cm; maximum of six times the character&#39;s height.</li><li><em>Standing Broad Jump:</em> (1d6 + half-level) × 30 cm.</li><li><em>Running Vertical Jump:</em> (1d3 + half-level) × 30 cm; maximum of one-and-a-half times the character&#39;s height.</li><li><em>Standing Vertical Jump:</em> 1 m.</li><li><em>Pole Vault:</em> Requires a 9 m running start and a pole 1.2–3 m longer than the character&#39;s height. Maximum distance equals one-and-a-half times the pole&#39;s length. A vault exceeding half the pole&#39;s length ends with the character prone; shorter vaults can be landed on the feet.</li></ul><hr><p><strong>Read Lips</strong> <em>(Rogue; Intelligence; −2; 2 points)</em> ◆ Discerning conversation from lip movement and body language. Requires line of sight within 9 m. On success, the character understands approximately 70% of a conversation — the gist, basic details, and simple names. Limited to the languages the character can speak.</p><hr><p><strong>Riding, Land</strong> <em>(General; Dexterity; 0; 1 point — Untrained permitted)</em> Competent handling of standard land mounts. Most actions do not require a check. Riding bareback imposes −2 to all riding checks and requires a check for actions that would otherwise be automatic. Exotic mounts impose an additional −2.</p><ul><li><em>Saddle Vault:</em> Mount a stationary creature as part of movement. Mounting without a saddle, with the creature already moving, or to have the creature act in the same round requires a check.</li><li><em>Jump:</em> A mounted creature can clear obstacles up to half its height or gaps up to twice its height without a check. Success on a check doubles jumping height and triples jumping distance.</li><li><em>Spur:</em> Increase mount speed by 6 on a successful check, maintainable for up to four rounds with continued checks.</li><li><em>Guide with Knees:</em> Free both hands automatically. A check is needed to stay mounted after taking damage.</li><li><em>Shield:</em> Drop down the mount&#39;s flank, using it as cover. AC improves by 6; attacks that hit instead strike the mount. Requires a check if armored or encumbered.</li><li><em>Leap from Saddle:</em> Leap up to 3 m and make a single melee attack during the mount&#39;s movement. A failed check causes the rider to fall for 1d3 damage.</li></ul><hr><p><strong>Set Snares and Traps</strong> <em>(Rogue/Warrior; Intelligence; −1; 1 point)</em> Construction and placement of traps and snares. A check is made at the end of the work period. A failed check produces a trap that the character believes is functional, but that fails when triggered. Characters proficient in Animal Lore gain +2 when setting game snares.</p><ul><li><em>Small Snare:</em> 6d10 minutes. Catches small game.</li><li><em>Large Snare:</em> 2d4 hours with at least one assistant. −2 to check. Catches up to large-sized creatures.</li><li><em>Man Trap:</em> Constructed from available materials; complexity determines time. −4 to check for a single constructor.</li></ul><hr><p><strong>Survival</strong> <em>(General; Wisdom; 0; 1 point — Untrained permitted)</em> Basic survival techniques in hostile terrain. A survivalist reduces the chance of becoming lost by 5% per skill point.</p><ul><li><em>Forage:</em> Locate food and water for a number of human-sized creatures equal to the margin of success. Requires one hour. Terrain difficulty varies: dense forest +4, desert −4.</li><li><em>Fire-Building:</em> Build a fire in 2d10 minutes without a tinderbox. Wet tinder increases time to 3d10 minutes and requires a check.</li><li><em>Sense Direction:</em> Concentrate 1d6 rounds. Success yields accurate direction. A standard failure gives a 90-degree error; a natural 20 gives the opposite direction. Bonuses: visible sun or moon +2, large visible landmark +2. Penalties: night −2, fog or poor visibility −2, underground −4. Duergar and Duardeen automatically know their direction underground. The GM rolls in secret.</li><li><em>Weather Sense:</em> Predict conditions for the next 6 hours on success. A failed check gives a false reading. One check every 6 hours; each additional 6-hour observation period adds +1 to the next check.</li></ul><hr><p><strong>Swimming</strong> <em>(General; Strength; 0; 1 point — Untrained permitted)</em> Full swimming rules appear in Chapter 10. A trained swimmer handles all but hazardous conditions without a check. Untrained characters can float in calm water but struggle in anything else.</p><hr><p><strong>Use Rope</strong> <em>(General; Dexterity; 0; 1 point — Untrained permitted)</em> Knots, lashing, and rope techniques. A trained character can bind a target such that no human-sized creature with Strength below 20 can break free. A failed check allows anyone with Strength 18+ to break free, or escape with a Dexterity check at −12. A trained character gains +2 to attack rolls with a lasso and +2 to climb checks when using an anchored rope.</p><hr><h3 id="class-restricted-skills" tabindex="-1"><strong>CLASS-RESTRICTED SKILLS</strong> <a class="header-anchor" href="#class-restricted-skills" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;**CLASS-RESTRICTED SKILLS**&quot;">​</a></h3><hr><p><strong>Appraise</strong> <em>(Rogue; Intelligence; 0; 1 point)</em> Assessment of valuable objects — antiques, art, gems, and crafted items — including detection of counterfeits. Requires one minute of study. A successful check gives an accurate reading within a 10% margin. A natural 20 gives a wildly inaccurate result. The GM rolls in secret.</p><hr><p><strong>Blind-Fight</strong> <em>(Rogue/Warrior; no attribute check; 2 points)</em> Trained compensation for poor visibility. Eliminates the AC penalty in darkness. Reduces attack penalties for dim and no lighting by half. Reduces the attack penalty against invisible opponents to −2. Movement in total darkness increases to half speed rather than one-third. Applies to melee only; ranged penalties are unaffected. This skill has only one level of investment — further points provide no benefit.</p><hr><p><strong>Cross-Country Running</strong> <em>(Warrior; Constitution; −6; 1 point)</em> Sustained movement techniques for open terrain. A trained runner can march at twice their movement rate for an 8-hour day and continue on successive days with a successful check. After more than one hour of cross-country running, the character suffers −1 to attack rolls until they rest.</p><hr><p><strong>Forgery</strong> <em>(Rogue; Dexterity; −1; 1 point)</em> Creation and detection of handwritten forgeries. Requires a reference document. Forging a specific person&#39;s signature is −2; forging an entire document in their handwriting is −3. The GM rolls in secret — a character always believes their work is convincing. Detection: standard documents pass most inspections on success; only those intimately familiar with the document type or the writer&#39;s hand can identify them on a failed check.</p><hr><p><strong>Healing</strong> <em>(Priest; Wisdom; −2; 2 points)</em> ◆ Advanced care through natural means.</p><ul><li><em>Emergency Treatment:</em> Restore 1d3 hit points if applied within 10 minutes of injury. One use per patient per day.</li><li><em>Long-Term Care:</em> A healer can tend up to 6 patients. Patients under care recover 1 hit point per day regardless of activity, 2 per day at complete rest, or 3 per day at complete rest if the healer is also trained in Herbalism.</li><li><em>Poison Treatment:</em> If the healer works continuously for 5 rounds beginning within one round of a character being poisoned (wound or bloodstream delivery only), the patient gains +2 to their saving throw. Interruption removes the bonus.</li><li><em>Disease:</em> A full day of treatment followed by a successful check reduces any variable damage and duration to a minimum. Magical diseases can be diagnosed but require magical treatment.</li></ul><hr><p><strong>Read/Write Language</strong> <em>(Rogue/Wizard; 1 point)</em> Literacy in a language the character already speaks. Unless a language&#39;s script derives from Common or a language the character already reads, literacy is not included in the Modern Language skill. One skill point per language.</p><hr><p><strong>Spellcraft</strong> <em>(Wizard; Intelligence; −2; 1 point)</em> ◆ Identification of magical effects in progress or already active. A successful check while observing active casting identifies the spell. Post-casting identification of an active effect is possible if the effect is observable. Specialist Mages gain +3 to identify spells from their school and −3 to identify spells from their opposed school.</p><hr><p><strong>Tracking</strong> <em>(Rogue/Warrior; Wisdom; −6; 2 points)</em> Functions identically to the Ranger class skill, with an additional built-in −6 penalty for non-Rangers reflecting the extreme difficulty of the skill outside dedicated wilderness training. Rangers are automatically proficient; further skill investment gives them the standard trained bonus on top of their class ability.</p><hr><h3 id="knowledge-skills" tabindex="-1"><strong>KNOWLEDGE SKILLS</strong> <a class="header-anchor" href="#knowledge-skills" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;**KNOWLEDGE SKILLS**&quot;">​</a></h3><p>Knowledge skills cover bodies of information. A single skill point grants proficiency in one knowledge field. Checks should be called only when the answer is specific and not commonly known. A character either knows the answer or does not — no rerolls are permitted unless time is spent researching.</p><h3 id="table-7-2-knowledge-skills" tabindex="-1"><strong>Table 7.2: Knowledge Skills</strong> <a class="header-anchor" href="#table-7-2-knowledge-skills" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;**Table 7.2: Knowledge Skills**&quot;">​</a></h3><table tabindex="0"><thead><tr><th>Skill</th><th>Classes</th><th>Attribute</th><th>Difficulty</th><th>Cost</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Ancient History</td><td>Priest/Rogue/Wizard</td><td>Intelligence</td><td>−1</td><td>1 point</td></tr><tr><td>Animal Lore</td><td>Warrior/Priest</td><td>Intelligence</td><td>0</td><td>1 point</td></tr><tr><td>Astrology</td><td>Priest/Wizard</td><td>Intelligence</td><td>0</td><td>2 points</td></tr><tr><td>Engineering</td><td>General</td><td>Intelligence</td><td>−3</td><td>2 points</td></tr><tr><td>Gaming</td><td>Rogue/Warrior</td><td>Charisma</td><td>0</td><td>1 point</td></tr><tr><td>Herbalism</td><td>Priest/Rogue/Wizard</td><td>Intelligence</td><td>−2</td><td>2 points</td></tr><tr><td>Local History</td><td>Priest/Rogue</td><td>Intelligence</td><td>0</td><td>1 point</td></tr><tr><td>Navigation</td><td>General</td><td>Intelligence</td><td>−2</td><td>1 point</td></tr><tr><td>Religion</td><td>Priest/Wizard</td><td>Wisdom</td><td>0</td><td>1 point</td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong>Ancient History.</strong> Esoteric and lost knowledge of a specific culture, civilization, or people. Deeper study of events far beyond common teaching.</p><p><strong>Animal Lore.</strong> Natural animals and their behavior. A successful check allows the character to assess an animal&#39;s disposition. A failure reveals nothing; a failure of 5+ gives a false reading. Magical animals impose a difficulty modifier based on rarity. Also allows accurate animal calls — physically plausible only, and convincing enough to fool creatures not intimately familiar with the real sound.</p><p><strong>Astrology.</strong> The stars, heavenly bodies, and their patterns. Allows prediction of general events up to 30 days forward on a successful check. Results are broad and directional, not precise. Grants +1 to Navigation when stars are visible.</p><p><strong>Engineering</strong> ◆. Design of complex structures and machines — bridges, catapults, dams, siege equipment. This skill covers design and supervision, not construction. Also allows the detection of structural flaws and the operation of complex machinery.</p><p><strong>Gaming.</strong> Games of chance and skill — deep knowledge of probabilities, techniques, and detection of cheating. A check can be made to cheat successfully; a result of 17–20, regardless of success or failure, means the character is caught.</p><p><strong>Herbalism.</strong> Identification of natural plants and preparation of non-magical mixtures, including poisons from natural substances. When combined with Healing, it increases daily recovery under the healer&#39;s care and expands poison treatment to all poison types.</p><p><strong>Local History.</strong> Detailed and esoteric knowledge of a specific region — facts beyond common knowledge. A successful check while using this knowledge in a social context grants +2 to Charisma for the encounter.</p><p><strong>Navigation.</strong> Wind, stars, and currents. Reduces the chance of becoming lost by 5% on land and 20% at sea.</p><p><strong>Religion.</strong> Doctrinal knowledge of one&#39;s own faith and neighboring religious traditions. Additional skill points extend knowledge to more distant or obscure faiths.</p><p><strong>Languages, Ancient</strong> <em>(Priest/Wizard).</em> Obscure languages few creatures still speak — dead tongues, planar dialects, and archaic scripts. One skill point per language.</p><p><strong>Languages, Modern</strong> <em>(General).</em> A spoken language with an available teacher. One skill point per language. Literacy is not included unless the script derives from a language the character already reads. A character cannot exceed their Intelligence language limit regardless of skill investment.</p><hr><h3 id="performance-skills" tabindex="-1"><strong>PERFORMANCE SKILLS</strong> <a class="header-anchor" href="#performance-skills" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;**PERFORMANCE SKILLS**&quot;">​</a></h3><p>Performance skills encompass public showmanship and entertainment. A street performer in a modest town earns copper pieces equal to their margin of success each day; in a city, silver. Notable performers eventually attract private engagements. Each performance type is a separate skill.</p><h3 id="table-7-3-performance-skills" tabindex="-1"><strong>Table 7.3: Performance Skills</strong> <a class="header-anchor" href="#table-7-3-performance-skills" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;**Table 7.3: Performance Skills**&quot;">​</a></h3><table tabindex="0"><thead><tr><th>Skill</th><th>Classes</th><th>Attribute</th><th>Difficulty</th><th>Cost</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Dance</td><td>General</td><td>Dexterity</td><td>0</td><td>1 point — Untrained permitted</td></tr><tr><td>Instrument</td><td>General</td><td>Dexterity</td><td>−1</td><td>1 point per instrument</td></tr><tr><td>Juggling</td><td>General</td><td>Dexterity</td><td>−1</td><td>1 point</td></tr><tr><td>Singing</td><td>General</td><td>Charisma</td><td>0</td><td>1 point — Untrained permitted</td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong>Juggling.</strong> Basic performances require no check unless large objects are involved. A trained Rogue may use Juggling to catch small thrown weapons (daggers, darts) aimed at them or within reach: an attack roll using base Attack Bonus modified only by Dexterity against AC 10. A free hand is required and the Rogue must be aware of the attack. Failure causes the weapon to deal damage even if the original attack would have missed.</p><hr><h3 id="trade-skills" tabindex="-1"><strong>TRADE SKILLS</strong> <a class="header-anchor" href="#trade-skills" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;**TRADE SKILLS**&quot;">​</a></h3><p>Trade skills cover professional crafts and practical occupations. One skill point grants proficiency. A trained character can supervise untrained assistants, allowing them to contribute to the work without requiring their own proficiency check. This list is representative, not exhaustive — the GM should permit reasonable trade skills not listed here.</p><p>Skills marked ◆ cannot be attempted untrained under any circumstances.</p><h3 id="table-7-4-trade-skills" tabindex="-1"><strong>Table 7.4: Trade Skills</strong> <a class="header-anchor" href="#table-7-4-trade-skills" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;**Table 7.4: Trade Skills**&quot;">​</a></h3><table tabindex="0"><thead><tr><th>Skill</th><th>Classes</th><th>Attribute</th><th>Difficulty</th><th>Cost</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Agriculture</td><td>General</td><td>Intelligence</td><td>0</td><td>1 point</td></tr><tr><td>Armorer</td><td>Warrior</td><td>Intelligence</td><td>−2</td><td>2 points</td></tr><tr><td>Artist (Field)</td><td>General</td><td>Intelligence</td><td>0</td><td>1 point</td></tr><tr><td>Blacksmith</td><td>General</td><td>Strength</td><td>0</td><td>1 point</td></tr><tr><td>Bowyer/Fletcher</td><td>General</td><td>Dexterity</td><td>−1</td><td>1 point</td></tr><tr><td>Brewing</td><td>General</td><td>Intelligence</td><td>0</td><td>1 point</td></tr><tr><td>Carpentry</td><td>General</td><td>Strength</td><td>0</td><td>1 point</td></tr><tr><td>Cobbler</td><td>General</td><td>Dexterity</td><td>0</td><td>1 point</td></tr><tr><td>Cooking</td><td>General</td><td>Intelligence</td><td>0</td><td>1 point</td></tr><tr><td>Gemcutting</td><td>Rogue</td><td>Dexterity</td><td>−2</td><td>2 points</td></tr><tr><td>Leatherworking</td><td>General</td><td>Dexterity</td><td>0</td><td>1 point</td></tr><tr><td>Mason</td><td>General</td><td>Strength</td><td>−2</td><td>1 point</td></tr><tr><td>Mining</td><td>Warrior</td><td>Wisdom</td><td>−3</td><td>2 points</td></tr><tr><td>Seamstress/Tailor</td><td>General</td><td>Dexterity</td><td>−1</td><td>1 point</td></tr><tr><td>Shipwright</td><td>General</td><td>Intelligence</td><td>−2</td><td>2 points</td></tr><tr><td>Weaponsmith</td><td>Warrior</td><td>Intelligence</td><td>−3</td><td>3 points</td></tr><tr><td>Weaving</td><td>General</td><td>Intelligence</td><td>0</td><td>1 point</td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong>Armorer</strong> ◆. Creation of metal armors. A check at the end of the crafting period; failure produces flawed armor with −1 to AC, a flaw the wearer usually cannot detect. Plate armor requires the recipient to be present for a week of fitting. Proficient armorers can detect flaws by inspection.</p><p><strong>Artist (Field).</strong> Specialization in a chosen medium — painting, sculpting, etc. Grants +1 to Appraise when assessing art and to checks related to music and acting.</p><p><strong>Mining.</strong> Extraction of ore and mineral resources, including assessment of tunnel stability. Duardeen and Duergar characters gain +2 to this skill.</p><p><strong>Weaponsmith</strong> ◆. Creation of bladed weapons and edged tools. The greatest difficulty craft skill on this list. A failed check produces a weapon that snaps under stress — a natural 1 on an attack roll — or one that deals −1 damage permanently. A skilled weaponsmith can identify flaws in weapons before purchase.</p>',119)])])}const g=t(r,[["render",s]]);export{m as __pageData,g as default};
